"{\"uid\": \"theatlantic.com-science-archive-2024-07-seine-swimming-triathlon-olympics-679312\", \"entities\": [{\"sentence\": \"Its water quality is still quite murky.\", \"from\": 0, \"to\": 39, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Last night, in Paris, thunderstorms threatened to pummel the Seine.\", \"from\": 43, \"to\": 110, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 58, \"end\": 63, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}, {\"begin\": 104, \"end\": 109, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The men's triathlon had already beenpostponedafter levels of bacteria in the river measured high, and more rain would have made it worse.\", \"from\": 111, \"to\": 248, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Downpours can sweep trash and grime into the river and overwhelm treatment plants as well as oldcombined pipeswhere stormwater mingles with wastewater; even the massive tanks Paris installed to keep that mess from pouring into the Seine can bebested by pounding rains.\", \"from\": 249, \"to\": 517, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 424, \"end\": 429, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}, {\"begin\": 480, \"end\": 485, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"And rain did fall in the hours just before the triathletes dove into the river today.\", \"from\": 518, \"to\": 603, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"It slowed as they prepared to race, plunging goggles into the water before sealing them against their face.\", \"from\": 604, \"to\": 711, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"But samplestaken yesterdayfrom the Seine apparently passed the water-quality tests, though an independent monitoring groupclassifiedthe health risks as being in a murky \\\"gray zone\\\" based on samples taken around the same time.\", \"from\": 712, \"to\": 937, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 747, \"end\": 752, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Paris wanted to prove that its years-long gamble on the river has paid off, and today, the city and the athletes are flush with victory (and hopefully notE.\", \"from\": 938, \"to\": 1094, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 938, \"end\": 943, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"coli).\", \"from\": 1095, \"to\": 1101, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The problem that the city faces-the very old, very tricky, very ongoing job of wrangling sewage-is not a uniquely Parisian challenge: Systems that dump waste into the river during heavy rain are common in theUnited States, theUnited Kingdom, and beyond.\", \"from\": 1105, \"to\": 1358, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"But Paris happens to be a place that recently made particularly loud public promises about curbing this type of pollution.\", \"from\": 1359, \"to\": 1481, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1363, \"end\": 1368, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"The city managed to fulfill those promises, and proved that even a famously dirty river can be made swimmable-just not necessarily on any one particular day.\", \"from\": 1482, \"to\": 1639, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The Seine met its technical marks, but only by a hair.\", \"from\": 1643, \"to\": 1697, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1647, \"end\": 1652, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Under World Triathlon rules, for the athletes to swim, competition waters must fulfill certain laboratory criteria, and also pass a sniff test and a visual once-over.\", \"from\": 1698, \"to\": 1864, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 1704, \"end\": 1719, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_Triathlon\", \"score\": 0.9999998209405181, \"rank\": 1.790591521208525e-07, \"text\": \"World Triathlon\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_Triathlon\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/World_Triathlon\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Athletescannotjump into waters that reek of phenol or that are slicked with oil, thick with birds or algal blooms, ribboned with sewage, or studded with garbage.\", \"from\": 1865, \"to\": 2026, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The waters must also meet particular limits forE.\", \"from\": 2027, \"to\": 2076, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"coliandEnterococcus, a genus of bacteria that proliferates in animals' intestines and serves asa proxyfor disease-causing bacteria that travel in feces.\", \"from\": 2077, \"to\": 2229, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Some samples from the Seinefailed to meet these standards-whichexceed the limits recommendedby the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency-duringtests last monthafter heavy rains,andsome samples collected this weekrevealedE.\", \"from\": 2230, \"to\": 2451, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"colilevels that were unacceptably high following a downpour that made for asoggy opening ceremony.\", \"from\": 2452, \"to\": 2550, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The results from additional, more recent samples are not yet publicly available but are reportedly coming soon.\", \"from\": 2554, \"to\": 2665, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Testing takes time.\", \"from\": 2666, \"to\": 2685, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Because bacteria are living organisms, the best way to measure them is to let them grow and replicate, which involves incubating a sample for about 24 hours before analyzing it, Alice Volpitta, the lead water-quality scientist at the advocacy group Blue Water Baltimore, told me.\", \"from\": 2686, \"to\": 2965, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 2864, \"end\": 2869, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portrayals_of_Alice_in_Wonderland\", \"score\": 0.9974589801686008, \"rank\": 0.002547493061756827, \"text\": \"Alice\", \"types\": [\"Q95074\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portrayals_of_Alice_in_Wonderland\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Portrayals_of_Alice_in_Wonderland\"}, {\"begin\": 2935, \"end\": 2945, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ocean_Productions\", \"score\": 0.9999999490046334, \"rank\": 5.099502944107237e-08, \"text\": \"Blue Water\", \"types\": [\"Q4830453\", \"Q43229\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ocean_Productions\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Ocean_Productions\"}, {\"begin\": 2946, \"end\": 2955, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Baltimore\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 8.796015134741482e-17, \"text\": \"Baltimore\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Baltimore\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Baltimore\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Once that sample is ready, \\\"it's a look into the past, but it does not tell us what's happening right now,\\\" she said.\", \"from\": 2966, \"to\": 3083, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"That matters when we are talking about sewage ecosystems, because things can change at the drop of a hat.\\\"\", \"from\": 3084, \"to\": 3191, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The river is probably the cleanest it's been in centuries.\", \"from\": 3195, \"to\": 3253, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Well before swimming in the Seine was prohibited about 100 years ago, the river had already earned a reputation as a fetid open sewer.\", \"from\": 3254, \"to\": 3388, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3282, \"end\": 3287, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"As Elaine SciolinowroteinThe Seine: The River That Made Paris, in the 18th century, the water was \\\"blood-red from animal carcasses, brown from garbage and excrement, black from tanners' dyes and rot.\\\"\", \"from\": 3389, \"to\": 3589, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3392, \"end\": 3398, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Elaine_Benes\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.0301703787913967e-29, \"text\": \"Elaine\", \"types\": [\"Q95074\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Elaine_Benes\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Elaine_Benes\"}, {\"begin\": 3418, \"end\": 3423, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"score\": 0.99999727783695, \"rank\": 2.7221705738310776e-06, \"text\": \"Seine\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Seine\"}, {\"begin\": 3445, \"end\": 3450, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the 19th century, Baron Haussmann and his brigade of engineers and laborers expanded the sewer network, and once-open trenches were hidden underground.\", \"from\": 3590, \"to\": 3744, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 3611, \"end\": 3626, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5164333075647571e-43, \"text\": \"Baron Haussmann\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Haussmann's_renovation_of_Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"But some trenches still disgorged untreated wastewater into the river.\", \"from\": 3745, \"to\": 3815, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Downstream, where almost 1 million pounds of sewage entered the water each day, the water was reportedly sluggish and black; debris mounded into mud shoals that resisted dredging, as the historian Donald Reid hasnoted.\", \"from\": 3816, \"to\": 4034, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 4013, \"end\": 4024, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\", \"score\": 0.999999998279236, \"rank\": 1.3091982177674626e-09, \"text\": \"Donald Reid\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Donald_Reid_Medal\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"In the 1870s, theIrish Builder, a trade journal that catered to the engineering-minded,reported thatthe river was laden with liquids from foundries, rubber makers, and laundries-which caused the river to bubble with 132 tons of soap each year-as well as refuse from the process of making poudrette, a fertilizer fashioned from dried excrement.\", \"from\": 4035, \"to\": 4378, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Well into the 20th century, pollution was blamed for waters goneominously fallow.\", \"from\": 4379, \"to\": 4460, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Over the past several years, Parisput more than $1.5 billionintoseveral types of improvements, including the tanks meant to catch sewer overflows, to shore up the river before the Games.\", \"from\": 4461, \"to\": 4647, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Even when they are not facing the spotlight of a major international spectacle, places with combined sewage and rainwater pipes have been attempting to stave off spills.\", \"from\": 4651, \"to\": 4820, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Some placesbuildretention ponds or tunnels; others rely on sensors to redirect water by opening or closing gates.\", \"from\": 4821, \"to\": 4934, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"These tactics can slash the number of spills and the volume of sullied water they introduce, but data are patchy.\", \"from\": 4935, \"to\": 5048, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In the U.S.,700 municipalitiesstill have these combined pipes; as of two decades ago, they were disgorging850 billion gallonsof fouled water each year, according to the EPA.\", \"from\": 5049, \"to\": 5222, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 5218, \"end\": 5221, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.4871887161463013e-34, \"text\": \"EPA\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q327333\", \"Q24229398\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_States_Environmental_Protection_Agency\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"(The Government Accountability Officehas pushed the EPAto release updated numbers by next year.)\", \"from\": 5223, \"to\": 5319, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In the meantime, the pipes are doing what they were designed to do.\", \"from\": 5323, \"to\": 5390, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Overflows function as \\\"emergency escape hatches, basically off-ramps for sewage\\\" when a system sees a big influx of water, Volpitta said.\", \"from\": 5391, \"to\": 5528, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Tamping down on them helps keep rivers cleaner, but it also creates different hazards: When combined sewers can not spit up water as they previously did (a problem that will only worsen as water levelsinch higherin a wetter, flood-prone world), pipes sometimes belch their contents into streets or basements.\", \"from\": 5529, \"to\": 5837, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"One of experts' main ideas, beyond lining, replacing, or separating pipes, for addressing these issues is maximizing spongy intercepting ponds, rain gardens,reedbeds, and other green infrastructure to hold or slow water and \\\"minimize the shock of rainfall into the system,\\\" says Franco Montalto, a professor of civil, architectural, and environmental engineering at Drexel University, in Philadelphia.\", \"from\": 5839, \"to\": 6240, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6118, \"end\": 6124, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_people\", \"score\": 0.6821212869804922, \"rank\": 0.4660103204372077, \"text\": \"Franco\", \"types\": [\"Q41710\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_people\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_people\"}, {\"begin\": 6125, \"end\": 6133, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\", \"score\": 0.9502184846949333, \"rank\": 0.052295822416117306, \"text\": \"Montalto\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\"}, {\"begin\": 6205, \"end\": 6222, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Drexel_University\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 3.548594958382974e-22, \"text\": \"Drexel University\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q3918\", \"Q24229398\", \"Q2385804\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Drexel_University\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Drexel_University\"}, {\"begin\": 6227, \"end\": 6239, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.618938548180873e-19, \"text\": \"Philadelphia\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Philadelphia incentivizes sponginess bycharging for impervious surfaces; bit by bit, Montalto told me, cities could also recontour streets to promote short-term flooding of parks or athletic fields instead of roads that dump into sewers.\", \"from\": 6241, \"to\": 6478, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6241, \"end\": 6253, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.618938548180873e-19, \"text\": \"Philadelphia\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Philadelphia\"}, {\"begin\": 6326, \"end\": 6334, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\", \"score\": 0.9502184846949333, \"rank\": 0.052295822416117306, \"text\": \"Montalto\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Montalto_delle_Marche\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Urban rivers are generally healthier now than they were a few decades ago.\", \"from\": 6482, \"to\": 6556, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"But at the moment, \\\"there is no such thing as a risk-free environment in an urban waterway,\\\" Volpitta told me.\", \"from\": 6557, \"to\": 6667, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"\\\"We may see lower bacteria levels but are still exposing people to pathogens and toxins.\\\"\", \"from\": 6668, \"to\": 6757, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"In New York, for instance, Hudson River Parkshares daily measurementsof water temperature, cloudiness, and more, and worked with several partners to producea public-facing calendarthat indicates likely risks of bacteria connected to sewer overflows.\", \"from\": 6758, \"to\": 7007, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 6761, \"end\": 6769, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\", \"score\": 0.9999998030516702, \"rank\": 1.9694843565614114e-07, \"text\": \"New York\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/New_York_City\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"(The calendar draws on data gathered a few years ago, on rainy spring days.)\", \"from\": 7008, \"to\": 7084, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Most days in the past year have been low risk; about three dozen have been high (the model does not allow for zero).\", \"from\": 7085, \"to\": 7201, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"The goal for any river, Volpitta said, is \\\"more swimmable days overall.\\\"\", \"from\": 7202, \"to\": 7274, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Which is, to be fair, what Paris has managed-somedays when the river is swimmable.\", \"from\": 7275, \"to\": 7357, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 7302, \"end\": 7307, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 2.5840203743392823e-17, \"text\": \"Paris\", \"types\": [\"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Paris\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Claire Robertson, an ecologist and the Oxford Rivers project officer at the England-based environmental charity Thames21, agrees that people belong in rivers.\", \"from\": 7361, \"to\": 7519, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 7368, \"end\": 7377, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\", \"score\": 0.5848012763138514, \"rank\": 0.7099825874552865, \"text\": \"Robertson\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\"}, {\"begin\": 7400, \"end\": 7406, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Oxford\", \"score\": 0.9857224612563421, \"rank\": 0.014484339404260534, \"text\": \"Oxford\", \"types\": [\"Q43229\", \"Q3918\", \"Q24229398\", \"Q2385804\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Oxford\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/University_of_Oxford\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Vienna's Danube, Munich's Isar, and many rivers squiggling across the U.K. and France all have a long history of hosting swimmers.\", \"from\": 7520, \"to\": 7650, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 7520, \"end\": 7526, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vienna\", \"score\": 0.9999999999818101, \"rank\": 1.8555206913302067e-11, \"text\": \"Vienna\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vienna\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Vienna\"}, {\"begin\": 7529, \"end\": 7535, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Danube\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 1.5165321470070007e-27, \"text\": \"Danube\", \"types\": [\"Q47521\", \"Q4022\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Danube\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Danube\"}, {\"begin\": 7537, \"end\": 7543, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\", \"score\": 0.9999999960673449, \"rank\": 3.931830973657355e-09, \"text\": \"Munich\", \"types\": [\"Q515\", \"Q486972\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Munich\"}, {\"begin\": 7590, \"end\": 7594, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"score\": 0.999999731036987, \"rank\": 2.688662004561036e-07, \"text\": \"U.K.\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/United_Kingdom\"}, {\"begin\": 7599, \"end\": 7605, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Third_Republic\", \"score\": 0.551725410253379, \"rank\": 0.8030288536318944, \"text\": \"France\", \"types\": [\"Q6256\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Third_Republic\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/French_Third_Republic\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Robertson lives on a boat and swims in the Thames several times a week during the warm months-and sometimes during the colder ones too.\", \"from\": 7651, \"to\": 7786, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 7651, \"end\": 7660, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\", \"score\": 0.5848012763138514, \"rank\": 0.7099825874552865, \"text\": \"Robertson\", \"types\": [], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/Nate_Robertson\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"Swimming in urban rivers is \\\"absolutely a realistic goal,\\\" she told me.\", \"from\": 7787, \"to\": 7858, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Making a river swimmable depends on where you set the threshold and how swimmers think about individual risk tolerance-but planning a dunk for a specific day is tough.\", \"from\": 7859, \"to\": 8026, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"Good-enough water quality requires planning, funding, patience, and humility in the face of rain-which is unstoppable and utterly indifferent to medal counts.\", \"from\": 8027, \"to\": 8185, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"TheAtlantic.com \\u00a92026The Atlantic Monthly Group.\", \"from\": 8193, \"to\": 8241, \"entities\": [{\"begin\": 8218, \"end\": 8234, \"title\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Atlantic\", \"score\": 1.0, \"rank\": 0.0, \"text\": \"Atlantic Monthly\", \"types\": [\"Q41298\", \"Q386724\", \"Q234460\", \"Q1092563\"], \"wikid\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Atlantic\", \"dbpedia\": \"http://dbpedia.org/resource/The_Atlantic\"}]}, {\"sentence\": \"All Rights Reserved.\", \"from\": 8242, \"to\": 8262, \"entities\": []}, {\"sentence\": \"This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and the GooglePrivacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply\", \"from\": 8264, \"to\": 8352, \"entities\": []}]}"